[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Reasons for homelessness:[bold] trend[bold]Source: P1E stats[bold]&#xa0;[bold]At the same time as homelessness due to loss of private rented accommodation is increasing, local authorities are finding it more and 
[normal]more difficult to procure reasonable quality temporary accommodation in and around London. The number of households being place
[normal]d in temporary accommodation has continued to increase since 2011 but the availability of 
[normal]temporary private rented accommodation 
[normal]has dropped as private landlords leave the ‘temporary accommodation’ sector for the 
[normal]buoyant
[normal] rental market in the non-benefit sector. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As the proportion of private sector temporary accommodation decreases, l
[normal]ocal authorities are working hard to maintain the existing supply in a difficult market 
[normal]but
[normal] are increasingly being forced to look out of London.
[normal] The concerns in respect of child safety and welfare in out of borough placements are well documented and of par
[normal]amount 
[normal]importance. Local
[normal] authorities are likely to have to meet the shortfalls in rent for families in unaffordable temporary accommodation
[normal], with 
[normal]more 
[normal]households being moved out of London as the situation is not sustainable. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Options for local authorities
[normal] are therefore extremely limited, and near non-existent for accommodating larger families. 
[normal]B
[normal]ed and breakfast (B&amp;B) accommodation is
[normal] already expensive
[normal] and nightly rate prices are increasing as 
[normal]councils have little choice but to use them
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Local authorities
[normal] worked hard to meet the Government’s temporary accommodation reduction target 
[normal]December 2010
[normal] deadline
[normal], however its use has risen steadily over the past year
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Source: P1E stats. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The increase in B&amp;B use is particularly
[normal] steep as local authorities struggle to find additional affordable private sector temporary accommodation. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Number of Households in Bed and Breakfast Accommodation [bold]Source: P1E stats[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]TA Management Costs[bold]The 
[normal]t
[normal]emporary 
[normal]a
[normal]ccommodation subsidy arrang
[normal]ement for local a
[normal]uthorities includes a £40 per week managemen
[normal]t fee for placements in
[normal] accommodation leased 
[normal]from the
[normal] private rented sector. The government has agreed that when universal credit comes in this management fee will be p
[normal]aid  direct to boroughs rather than through Housing Benefit as it is at present. In the meantime, the overall benefit cap means that in many cases the fee is lost, leaving the local authority to cover the costs from their own increasingly limited funds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Larger Families and the overall Benefit Cap[bold]Under the 
[normal]Benefit C
[normal]ap, unless they are exempt, families with 
[normal]six
[normal] or more children receive only 50p Housing
[normal] Benefit. Whilst boroughs are working with households to help them get into employment, for single parents with young children, child care costs in 
[normal]London
[normal] make this very difficult. If the children are at school, part-time employment with hours that fit in 
[normal]with schools or self-employment may be the only options. If the parent is unable to get work, then they may be moved to a cheaper area. However, there are often reasons why this cannot happen. For example, it is difficult to move families with a child doin
[normal]g GSCEs or A-levels because of the disruption to a key stage of their education.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even if a family is moved to a cheaper location, they won't be able to afford the rent,
[normal] whether private, affordable or social
[normal]. 
[normal]This means that boroughs have to provide acco[bold]mmodation and subsidise the rent until they are able to obtain employment[bold]. DHP is currently being used to top rents up, but boroughs will have to subsidise rents even if DHP is not available
[normal]. 
[normal]Whilst the number of families subject to the 50p housing benefit
[normal] entitlement
[normal] is comparatively small, the financial burden
[normal] ultimately falls to the tax payer. 
[normal]These households are likely to be worse off on U
[normal]niversal 
[normal]C
[normal]redit
[normal]. At the very least, some form of transitional protection would be 
[normal]welcome. The
[normal] freedom provided by the Localism Act to discharge homeless duty into the private sector is not an option for these families as there is no attraction to landlords in accepting those whose rent cannot be covered.
[normal] 
[normal]Receiving
[normal] authorities would have 
[normal]neither th
[normal]e inclination, nor 
[normal]sufficient DHP 
[normal]funding
[normal] 
[normal]to 
[normal]top up rents for 
[normal]households exported from more expensive areas. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As capping has not finished and our analysis continues, the number of families awarded 50p Housing Benefit is likely to rise. Based on 315 cappe
[normal]d cases, 
[normal]Harrow
[normal] has 
[normal]13 lone parents who have children in key stages of education
[normal] and 8
[normal] families identified to date with only 50p H
[normal]ousing 
[normal]B
[normal]enefit.
[normal] 
[normal]With another 
[normal]80 cases
[normal] just come through, the
[normal] authority 
[normal]now
[normal] has
[normal] 
[normal]395 capped cases
[normal], some of which may be subject to the 50p HB rate. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Brent has 
[normal]to fund the shortfall for 
[normal]27 households subject to 50
[normal]p
[normal] HB 
[normal]and 
[normal]for
[normal] 
[normal]50 families 
[normal]in T
[normal]A 
[normal]losing 
[normal]more than 
[normal]£250 in HB.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ealing
[normal] has 1
[normal]1 families reduced to 50p with 10 children in th
[normal]e key stage exam ag
[normal]e range
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hammersmith and Fulham 
[normal]has 
[normal]17 households subject to 50p HB, with 10 more anticipated. Of these, 3 households have children 
[normal]in the key stage exam age range thus far. 
[normal]Some claimants are visibly ‘capable and employable’ but are adamant they do not want to work 
[normal]whilst expressing
[normal] resistance to moving to cheaper areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These issues also apply to families whose benefits have been capped by smaller amounts to a lesser degree
[normal] and the overall impact on local authorities needs to be considered
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Over
[normal] 4000 households are experiencing shortfalls in Housing Benefit
[normal] payments due to the bedroom tax in 
[normal]w
[normal]est London
[normal] which will inevitably lead to increased rent arrears.
[normal] The national press is already reporting the increase in rent arrears for Registered Providers.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is a lack of suitably sized accommodation for under occupiers facing a shortfall in their Housing
[normal] Benefit payments to downsize into. This will adversely affect social landlords’ rental income. The only real option available to many of these households is to try and downsize through a mutual exchange
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst allocation policies give under occupiers p
[normal]riority, the reality is that the number of tenants affected by the 
[normal]Bedroom T
[normal]ax exceeds the 
[normal]total
[normal] number of lettings for all categories in need, across the whole 
[normal]w
[normal]est London 
[normal]sub-
[normal]region last year. 
[normal]Although maximum priority is given to social tenants who are 
[normal]down-sizing, t
[normal]he fact that only 
[normal]234 
[normal]under occupiers moved last year indicates that the majority of the 4000+ households will be stuck
[normal] for many years 
[normal]being 
[normal]penali
[normal]s
[normal]ed for something they cannot swiftly change. 
[normal]We would welcome some transitional relief for te
[normal]nants who have applied to down size.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Local authorities are in a difficult position in estimating the effects of direct payments, based on the roll out progress of Universal Credit. The majority are expecting losses and making bad debt provision, particularly in the light of the pilot authorit
[normal]ies who suffered significant decreases in rental income. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are potential difficulties in ensuring payment of UC for TA cases in bed and breakfast placements for a few nights due to UC being assessed monthly, based on the claimant’s circumstances at 
[normal]the end of the month. If B&amp;B claimants do not make a UC claim when they enter B&amp;B they (or more likely the local authority) will not receive any payment towards the rent. Direct payments for 
[normal]temporary 
[normal]accommodation
[normal] placements
[normal] would be welcome.
[normal] 
[normal]D
[normal]irect payments 
[normal]for preventions in the PRS and PRSOs 
[normal]would 
[normal]give
[normal] landlords piece of mind and assist 
[normal]boroughs to
[normal] 
[normal]control the growth of TA, especially B&amp;B.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Concern has also been raised in respect of the DWP being able to cope with bulk rent increases; a situa
[normal]tion that will be exacerb
[normal]ated by landlords not being able to distinguish b
[normal]e
[normal]nefit claimants (which they can currently). 
[normal]&#xa0;
